>Vampire, Wraith, and Hunter were cool in a silly kind of way, but Mage and Werewolf always seemed preachy and stupid.
I've ranted about this in other boards before. Nerd culture--that's us, guys--in the US has always been contrarian. When the current popular culture is optimistic, we want grimderp. When popular culture is pessimistic, we want escape fantasy. In the 1970s the economy was in the toilet, the nation had just been defeated and humiliated in Vietnam, and nerds invented D&D as a simulator of Tolkien and high fantasy. In the 1980s and 90s, popculture in the US was mostly optimistic again. So nerds wanted Chinese cartoons about giant robot mayhem with morally ambiguous antihero protagonists and angsty werewolves preaching about muh acid rain and muh global warming. Since 9/11 popculture is pessimistic again, so much so that vampires and zombies, that personify and anthropomorphize death, decay, and entropy, have become a popculture mania--sort of like they were in the 70s, actually. So naturally nerds want Chinese moeblob cartoons, slice-of-life stories that drip with sugar, and "steampunk" alternate history Victorian adventure stories that are completely disconnected in every imaginable way from the here and now.

But I'm talking too much. Here, have a sexy unicorn. She's like a horse, but really horny.
